67int SHA224_Init(SHA256_CTX *sha) {
68 OPENSSL_memset(sha, 0, sizeof(SHA256_CTX));
69 sha->h[0] = 0xc1059ed8UL;
70 sha->h[1] = 0x367cd507UL;
71 sha->h[2] = 0x3070dd17UL;
72 sha->h[3] = 0xf70e5939UL;
73 sha->h[4] = 0xffc00b31UL;
74 sha->h[5] = 0x68581511UL;
75 sha->h[6] = 0x64f98fa7UL;
76 sha->h[7] = 0xbefa4fa4UL;
77 sha->md_len = SHA224_DIGEST_LENGTH;
78 return 1;
79}
80
81int SHA256_Init(SHA256_CTX *sha) {
82 OPENSSL_memset(sha, 0, sizeof(SHA256_CTX));
83 sha->h[0] = 0x6a09e667UL;
84 sha->h[1] = 0xbb67ae85UL;
85 sha->h[2] = 0x3c6ef372UL;
86 sha->h[3] = 0xa54ff53aUL;
87 sha->h[4] = 0x510e527fUL;
88 sha->h[5] = 0x9b05688cUL;
89 sha->h[6] = 0x1f83d9abUL;
90 sha->h[7] = 0x5be0cd19UL;
91 sha->md_len = SHA256_DIGEST_LENGTH;
92 return 1;
93}
94
95uint8_t *SHA224(const uint8_t *data, size_t len,
96 uint8_t out[SHA224_DIGEST_LENGTH]) {
97 SHA256_CTX ctx;
98 SHA224_Init(&ctx);
99 SHA224_Update(&ctx, data, len);
100 SHA224_Final(out, &ctx);
101 OPENSSL_cleanse(&ctx, sizeof(ctx));
102 return out;
103}
104
105uint8_t *SHA256(const uint8_t *data, size_t len,
106 uint8_t out[SHA256_DIGEST_LENGTH]) {
107 SHA256_CTX ctx;
108 SHA256_Init(&ctx);
109 SHA256_Update(&ctx, data, len);
110 SHA256_Final(out, &ctx);
111 OPENSSL_cleanse(&ctx, sizeof(ctx));
112 return out;
113}
114
115int SHA224_Update(SHA256_CTX *ctx, const void *data, size_t len) {
116 return SHA256_Update(ctx, data, len);
117}
118
119int SHA224_Final(uint8_t out[SHA224_DIGEST_LENGTH], SHA256_CTX *ctx) {
120 // SHA224_Init sets |ctx->md_len| to |SHA224_DIGEST_LENGTH|, so this has a
121 // smaller output.
122 return SHA256_Final(out, ctx);
123}

125#define DATA_ORDER_IS_BIG_ENDIAN
126
127#define HASH_CTX SHA256_CTX
128#define HASH_CBLOCK 64
129#define HASH_DIGEST_LENGTH 32
130
131// Note that FIPS180-2 discusses "Truncation of the Hash Function Output."
132// default: case below covers for it. It's not clear however if it's permitted
133// to truncate to amount of bytes not divisible by 4. I bet not, but if it is,
134// then default: case shall be extended. For reference. Idea behind separate
135// cases for pre-defined lenghts is to let the compiler decide if it's
136// appropriate to unroll small loops.
137//
138// TODO(davidben): The small |md_len| case is one of the few places a low-level
139// hash 'final' function can fail. This should never happen.
140#define HASH_MAKE_STRING(c, s) \
141 do { \
142 unsigned int nn; \
143 switch ((c)->md_len) { \
144 case SHA224_DIGEST_LENGTH: \
145 for (nn = 0; nn < SHA224_DIGEST_LENGTH / 4; nn++) { \
146 CRYPTO_store_u32_be((s), (c)->h[nn]); \
147 (s) += 4; \
148 } \
149 break; \
150 case SHA256_DIGEST_LENGTH: \
151 for (nn = 0; nn < SHA256_DIGEST_LENGTH / 4; nn++) { \
152 CRYPTO_store_u32_be((s), (c)->h[nn]); \
153 (s) += 4; \
154 } \
155 break; \
156 default: \
157 if ((c)->md_len > SHA256_DIGEST_LENGTH) { \
158 return 0; \
159 } \
160 for (nn = 0; nn < (c)->md_len / 4; nn++) { \
161 CRYPTO_store_u32_be((s), (c)->h[nn]); \
162 (s) += 4; \
163 } \
164 break; \
165 } \
166 } while (0)

180#ifndef SHA256_ASM
181static const uint32_t K256[64] = {
182 0x428a2f98UL, 0x71374491UL, 0xb5c0fbcfUL, 0xe9b5dba5UL, 0x3956c25bUL,
183 0x59f111f1UL, 0x923f82a4UL, 0xab1c5ed5UL, 0xd807aa98UL, 0x12835b01UL,
184 0x243185beUL, 0x550c7dc3UL, 0x72be5d74UL, 0x80deb1feUL, 0x9bdc06a7UL,
185 0xc19bf174UL, 0xe49b69c1UL, 0xefbe4786UL, 0x0fc19dc6UL, 0x240ca1ccUL,
186 0x2de92c6fUL, 0x4a7484aaUL, 0x5cb0a9dcUL, 0x76f988daUL, 0x983e5152UL,
187 0xa831c66dUL, 0xb00327c8UL, 0xbf597fc7UL, 0xc6e00bf3UL, 0xd5a79147UL,
188 0x06ca6351UL, 0x14292967UL, 0x27b70a85UL, 0x2e1b2138UL, 0x4d2c6dfcUL,
189 0x53380d13UL, 0x650a7354UL, 0x766a0abbUL, 0x81c2c92eUL, 0x92722c85UL,
190 0xa2bfe8a1UL, 0xa81a664bUL, 0xc24b8b70UL, 0xc76c51a3UL, 0xd192e819UL,
191 0xd6990624UL, 0xf40e3585UL, 0x106aa070UL, 0x19a4c116UL, 0x1e376c08UL,
192 0x2748774cUL, 0x34b0bcb5UL, 0x391c0cb3UL, 0x4ed8aa4aUL, 0x5b9cca4fUL,
193 0x682e6ff3UL, 0x748f82eeUL, 0x78a5636fUL, 0x84c87814UL, 0x8cc70208UL,
194 0x90befffaUL, 0xa4506cebUL, 0xbef9a3f7UL, 0xc67178f2UL};
195
196#define ROTATE(a, n) (((a) << (n)) | ((a) >> (32 - (n))))
197
198// FIPS specification refers to right rotations, while our ROTATE macro
199// is left one. This is why you might notice that rotation coefficients
200// differ from those observed in FIPS document by 32-N...
201#define Sigma0(x) (ROTATE((x), 30) ^ ROTATE((x), 19) ^ ROTATE((x), 10))
202#define Sigma1(x) (ROTATE((x), 26) ^ ROTATE((x), 21) ^ ROTATE((x), 7))
203#define sigma0(x) (ROTATE((x), 25) ^ ROTATE((x), 14) ^ ((x) >> 3))
204#define sigma1(x) (ROTATE((x), 15) ^ ROTATE((x), 13) ^ ((x) >> 10))
205
206#define Ch(x, y, z) (((x) & (y)) ^ ((~(x)) & (z)))
207#define Maj(x, y, z) (((x) & (y)) ^ ((x) & (z)) ^ ((y) & (z)))
208
209#define ROUND_00_15(i, a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h) \
210 do { \
211 T1 += h + Sigma1(e) + Ch(e, f, g) + K256[i]; \
212 h = Sigma0(a) + Maj(a, b, c); \
213 d += T1; \
214 h += T1; \
215 } while (0)
216
217#define ROUND_16_63(i, a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, X) \
218 do { \
219 s0 = X[(i + 1) & 0x0f]; \
220 s0 = sigma0(s0); \
221 s1 = X[(i + 14) & 0x0f]; \
222 s1 = sigma1(s1); \
223 T1 = X[(i) & 0x0f] += s0 + s1 + X[(i + 9) & 0x0f]; \
224 ROUND_00_15(i, a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h); \
225 } while (0)
226
227static void sha256_block_data_order(uint32_t *state, const uint8_t *data,
228 size_t num) {
229 uint32_t a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, s0, s1, T1;
230 uint32_t X[16];
231 int i;
232
233 while (num--) {
234 a = state[0];
235 b = state[1];
236 c = state[2];
237 d = state[3];
238 e = state[4];
239 f = state[5];
240 g = state[6];
241 h = state[7];
242
243 T1 = X[0] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
244 data += 4;
245 ROUND_00_15(0, a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h);
246 T1 = X[1] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
247 data += 4;
248 ROUND_00_15(1, h, a, b, c, d, e, f, g);
249 T1 = X[2] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
250 data += 4;
251 ROUND_00_15(2, g, h, a, b, c, d, e, f);
252 T1 = X[3] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
253 data += 4;
254 ROUND_00_15(3, f, g, h, a, b, c, d, e);
255 T1 = X[4] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
256 data += 4;
257 ROUND_00_15(4, e, f, g, h, a, b, c, d);
258 T1 = X[5] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
259 data += 4;
260 ROUND_00_15(5, d, e, f, g, h, a, b, c);
261 T1 = X[6] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
262 data += 4;
263 ROUND_00_15(6, c, d, e, f, g, h, a, b);
264 T1 = X[7] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
265 data += 4;
266 ROUND_00_15(7, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, a);
267 T1 = X[8] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
268 data += 4;
269 ROUND_00_15(8, a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h);
270 T1 = X[9] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
271 data += 4;
272 ROUND_00_15(9, h, a, b, c, d, e, f, g);
273 T1 = X[10] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
274 data += 4;
275 ROUND_00_15(10, g, h, a, b, c, d, e, f);
276 T1 = X[11] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
277 data += 4;
278 ROUND_00_15(11, f, g, h, a, b, c, d, e);
279 T1 = X[12] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
280 data += 4;
281 ROUND_00_15(12, e, f, g, h, a, b, c, d);
282 T1 = X[13] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
283 data += 4;
284 ROUND_00_15(13, d, e, f, g, h, a, b, c);
285 T1 = X[14] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
286 data += 4;
287 ROUND_00_15(14, c, d, e, f, g, h, a, b);
288 T1 = X[15] = CRYPTO_load_u32_be(data);
289 data += 4;
290 ROUND_00_15(15, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, a);
291
292 for (i = 16; i < 64; i += 8) {
293 ROUND_16_63(i + 0, a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, X);
294 ROUND_16_63(i + 1, h, a, b, c, d, e, f, g, X);
295 ROUND_16_63(i + 2, g, h, a, b, c, d, e, f, X);
296 ROUND_16_63(i + 3, f, g, h, a, b, c, d, e, X);
297 ROUND_16_63(i + 4, e, f, g, h, a, b, c, d, X);
298 ROUND_16_63(i + 5, d, e, f, g, h, a, b, c, X);
299 ROUND_16_63(i + 6, c, d, e, f, g, h, a, b, X);
300 ROUND_16_63(i + 7, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, a, X);
301 }
302
303 state[0] += a;
304 state[1] += b;
305 state[2] += c;
306 state[3] += d;
307 state[4] += e;
308 state[5] += f;
309 state[6] += g;
310 state[7] += h;
311 }
312}
313
314#endif // !SHA256_ASM
315
316void SHA256_TransformBlocks(uint32_t state[8], const uint8_t *data,
317 size_t num_blocks) {
318 sha256_block_data_order(state, data, num_blocks);
319}
